WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:05.644
Kyphoscoliosis is a structural chest wall
disorder that directly impacts ventilation.

2
00:00:06.505 --> 00:00:09.765
As a respiratory therapist, your focus is
not just the

3
00:00:09.765 --> 00:00:10.545
spine deformity.

4
00:00:11.085 --> 00:00:16.045
It's how that deformity restricts lung
expansion and leads to respiratory compromise.

5
00:00:16.305 --> 00:00:21.625
In kyphoscoliosis, abnormal curvature of
the spine changes the shape

6
00:00:21.625 --> 00:00:23.645
and mechanics of the thoracic cage.

7
00:00:24.194 --> 00:00:29.305
This reduces chest wall compliance,
meaning the lungs cannot expand

8
00:00:29.305 --> 00:00:30.844
fully during inspiration.

9
00:00:31.684 --> 00:00:35.084
The result is a restrictive lung pattern,
where lung volumes

10
00:00:35.084 --> 00:00:38.104
like tidal volume and vital capacity are
decreased.

11
00:00:38.884 --> 00:00:40.325
This leads to hypoventilation.

12
00:00:41.465 --> 00:00:45.424
Patients may initially compensate with
increased respiratory rate, but over

13
00:00:45.424 --> 00:00:50.424
time, ineffective ventilation can cause
chronic carbon dioxide retention and

14
00:00:50.424 --> 00:00:51.005
hypoxemia.

15
00:00:51.825 --> 00:00:56.205
Unlike obstructive diseases, airflow is
not the primary issue.

16
00:00:56.985 --> 00:00:58.625
Lung expansion is.

17
00:00:59.025 --> 00:01:02.185
Clinically, patients may present with
dyspnea on exertion,

18
00:01:02.985 --> 00:01:05.864
reduced exercise tolerance, shallow
breathing and,

19
00:01:06.025 --> 00:01:10.864
in advanced cases, signs of chronic
respiratory failure such as

20
00:01:10.864 --> 00:01:13.305
fatigue, morning headaches, or cyanosis.

21
00:01:14.205 --> 00:01:16.824
Breath sounds are often diminished, not
wheezing.

22
00:01:17.425 --> 00:01:22.044
Diagnostics typically show a restrictive
pattern on pulmonary function tests,

23
00:01:22.845 --> 00:01:27.684
reduced FVC with a normal or increased
FEV1-FVC ratio.

24
00:01:28.565 --> 00:01:32.165
ABGs may reveal chronic hypercapnia in
severe cases.

25
00:01:33.324 --> 00:01:36.724
Imaging confirms spinal deformity and
reduced thoracic volume.

26
00:01:37.824 --> 00:01:41.404
Management focuses on supporting
ventilation and preventing progression.

27
00:01:42.105 --> 00:01:46.245
Mild cases may require monitoring and
pulmonary rehab, but more

28
00:01:46.245 --> 00:01:51.285
advanced disease often requires
non-invasive ventilation, especially at night

29
00:01:51.285 --> 00:01:55.165
to improve alveolar ventilation and reduce
carbon dioxide retention.

30
00:01:56.105 --> 00:01:59.345
Oxygen therapy may be used cautiously, but
remember,

31
00:01:59.864 --> 00:02:02.125
these patients can rely on hypoxic drive.

32
00:02:02.845 --> 00:02:06.084
Always assess ventilation, not just
oxygenation.

33
00:02:06.485 --> 00:02:10.985
Red flags include rising PaCO2, worsening
fatigue,

34
00:02:11.645 --> 00:02:15.544
decreased mental status, and signs of
respiratory muscle exhaustion.

35
00:02:16.244 --> 00:02:20.404
These indicate impending ventilatory
failure and require escalation.

36
00:02:20.925 --> 00:02:23.925
From an RT perspective, your role is
critical.

37
00:02:24.565 --> 00:02:27.264
You assess work of breathing, monitor gas
exchange,

38
00:02:28.285 --> 00:02:32.524
initiate and manage ventilatory support,
and educate patients on long-

39
00:02:32.524 --> 00:02:33.925
term management strategies.

40
00:02:34.464 --> 00:02:39.505
Bottom line, kyphoscoliosis is a
restrictive problem that leads to

41
00:02:39.505 --> 00:02:40.184
hypoventilation.

42
00:02:41.184 --> 00:02:45.345
Always think, can this patient ventilate
effectively or are they

43
00:02:45.345 --> 00:02:46.125
heading toward failure?

